  "learnings_before": "- Valproate syrup is stocked in >90 % of district‑level pharmacies in Uganda, is inexpensive (~$0.08 per dose), and is the preferred first‑line agent for early‑onset focal and generalized epilepsies per the Ugandan National Essential Medicines List and ILAE 2022 guidelines.\n- Carbamazepine, lamotrigine, and phenytoin are classified as aromatic AEDs; patients with a history of drug‑induced skin rash are advised to avoid these agents.\n- Levetiracetam is non‑aromatic and has a low rash risk, but its dispersible tablets are intermittently available and cost ~2–3 times more per mg than valproate, making it a secondary option when valproate is contraindicated or unavailable.\n- Phenobarbital tablets are widely available but are associated with a high sedation rate (~30 % of children) and are less favored for children with cerebral palsy or developmental delay; it is reserved for refractory cases after failure of two optimized first‑line AEDs.\n- In children weighing 8–12 kg, the recommended valproate starting dose is 10 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrated by 5–10 mg/kg every 1–2 weeks to a target of 20–30 mg/kg/day, with baseline and 1‑month LFT/CBC monitoring; this dosing schema yields seizure‑free rates >70 % in local cohorts.\n- adherence scores based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data strongly predict seizure control; when adherence is low, the preferred strategy is to simplify regimens (single‑daily or twice‑daily dosing) rather than add additional agents.\n- Children with cerebral palsy and spastic tone benefit from AEDs with minimal sedation; valproate and levetiracetam are preferred over phenobarbital in this subgroup.\n- For infants with seizure onset <3 months and electrographic patterns of epileptic encephalopathy, early initiation of valproate (within the first month) is associated with improved developmental outcomes compared with delayed treatment.\n- Drug‑interaction profiles are critical: baclofen co‑administration does not significantly affect carbamazepine levels, whereas phenobarbital induces CYP enzymes and may reduce efficacy of concurrent antimalarials; valproate inhibition of CYP can increase plasma levels of co‑prescribed antiretrovirals.\n- Cost‑effectiveness analyses in Ugandan public health settings show that maintaining a child on valproate monotherapy (including monitoring) reduces total care costs by ~15 % relative to switching to phenobarbital or adding a second AED.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Valproate (syrup, tablet or dispersible) is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies, costs ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg dose, and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with focal or generalized seizures unless a contraindication is documented.  \n- Recommended therapeutic range for valproate is 20–30 mg/kg/day; doses outside this window should be adjusted only after confirming a serum valproate level < 50 µg/mL and normal baseline liver enzymes (ALT/AST < 2× ULN) and platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L.  \n- If a prescription section lists a drug and dose, the default action is to continue that regimen unchanged unless the clinical notes explicitly state a dose change, adverse event, or laboratory abnormality.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases when valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable or contraindicated; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because sedation occurs in ~30 % of such patients.  \n- Clobazam is not on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List for pediatric epilepsy and is rarely stocked; it should only be used if specifically prescribed by the clinician and serum clobazam levels are available (valproate co‑administration markedly increases clobazam concentrations).  \n- Levetiracetam is an effective non‑aromatic alternative; its cost is 2–3 × that of valproate and dispersible tablets may be intermittently unavailable, so it is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable in any formulation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) should be avoided in any child with a prior drug‑induced rash; if a rash history exists, the regimen defaults to valproate ± levetiracetam.  \n- Adherence ≥ 80 % (based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data) is required before adding a third agent; otherwise the strategy is to optimise dosing or simplify the existing regimen.  \n- Formulation substitution precedes any change of active drug: when syrup is unaffordable or out of stock, switch to equivalent tablets or dispersible formulation rather than selecting a different AED.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can raise plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals and zidovudine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑interaction checks are mandatory when co‑prescribing.  \n- In infants < 2 years, valproate carries a higher risk of hepatotoxicity and hyperammonemia; baseline and repeat LFTs and ammonia should be obtained before initiation and after any dose increase.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjuncts: phenobarbital (cheapest, widely available) is preferred over levetiracetam when an adjunct is required and no sedation or interaction contraindications exist.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window and no safety concerns are present, the recommended next step is to maintain the current valproate dose unchanged.",
